main event: On March 31, 1953, a student at Princeton University reported a sighting of a silver, stationary, circular object hovering silently and motionlessly for 15-30 minutes above a wooded area near Princeton, NJ.
interesting points: The object was described as approximately 30 feet in diameter and made of aluminum or some other silver-colored metal.
It was located approximately 150 feet from the observer at an altitude of 150 feet, and there was no sound associated with it.
The observer was certain that it was not a conventional aircraft, balloon, or any other known aerial object, and it appeared to be intelligently controlled despite no visible occupants.

The Air Technical Intelligence Center received about twenty reports from the East Coast in the past month, which were analyzed as being the planet Venus, suggesting a trend of misidentified celestial bodies.
The report was considered credible due to the observer's account and the characteristics of the object.
sighted object: a silver, stationary, circular object hovering silently and motionlessly
photographs: no photographs provided in the report
